diagnoses.name: Dry Eye Syndrome
diagnoses.comments: Chronic condition affecting eyes' ability to stay properly lubricated, contributing to difficulty focusing vision and potentially exacerbating stress, leading to obsessive-compulsive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Functional Dyspepsia
diagnoses.comments: A common digestive disorder, often linked to stress or anxiety, which could also correlate with obsessive-compulsive behavior.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.comments: An autoimmune disorder presenting with dry eyes and could potentially impact gastrointestinal health, indirectly related to dyspepsia.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder
diagnoses.comments: Can manifest physically with digestive problems (like dyspepsia) and psychologically with difficulty focusing and obsessive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD)
diagnoses.comments: While primarily a psychiatric condition, the stress and anxiety associated with OCD can manifest in physical symptoms like dyspepsia.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.comments: Severity can impact focus and give rise to OCD-like behaviors; certain medications for depression can cause dry eyes or dyspepsia.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.comments: Known for causing a wide range of symptoms, including difficulties with focus, dry eyes due to non-refreshing sleep, and gastrointestinal distress.

diagnoses.name: Blepharitis
diagnoses.comments: Inflammation of the eyelid which can cause dry eyes and difficulty focusing; may be linked indirectly to stress-related behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.comments: Thyroid disorders can cause wide-ranging symptoms including dry eyes, ocular vision problems, and gastrointestinal issues like dyspepsia.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes
diagnoses.comments: High blood sugar can lead to dry eyes and a host of other complications, including nerve damage that may influence gastrointestinal function.

diagnoses: Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (inappropriate insulin secretion could lead to hypoglycemia in some cases)
Vitamin Deficiencies (e.g., Vitamin B12, Vitamin D)

diagnoses: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (e.g., Crohn's disease, Ulcerative Colitis)

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that can lead to hypotension, angioedema, and respiratory distress.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition that causes episodes of severe swelling (angioedema), often with abdominal cramping and potential airway obstruction.

diagnoses.name: Non-hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: Swelling similar to hereditary angioedema but without the genetic component, often associated with allergic reactions.

diagnoses.name: Food Allergy
diagnoses.description: An allergic response to specific foods that can lead to abdominal cramps, incontinence, angioedema, nasal congestion, and hypotension.

diagnoses.name: Mastocytosis
diagnoses.description: A condition where mast cells accumulate in the skin and internal organs, causing symptoms like abdominal cramping, incontinence, and hypotension.

diagnoses.name: Carcinoid Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A group of symptoms caused by a carcinoid tumor that releases chemicals into the bloodstream, leading to abdominal cramps, hypotension, and flushing.

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS)
diagnoses.description: A chronic gastrointestinal disorder that can cause abdominal cramping, incontinence, and bloating.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain bacterial infections, characterized by sudden severe hypotension, rash, and multi-organ involvement.

diagnoses.name: Alpha-gal Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An allergic reaction to red meat and other products made from mammals, which can cause abdominal cramps, incontinence, and hypotension.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Capillary Leak Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder characterized by episodes of severe hypotension, hemoconcentration, and angioedema due to fluids leaking from small blood vessels into surrounding tissues.

diagnoses: Allergic Rhinitis Complicated by a Secondary Infection
Irritable Bowel Syndrome with Concomitant Upper Respiratory Tract Infection

diagnoses.name: Migraine with aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by recurrent attacks of moderate to severe pain. The aura may include visual disturbances such as scotoma, and speech disturbances (including aphasia), with symptoms like nausea and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Symptoms can include aphasia, weakness on one side of the body, and other neurological deficits.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA is a brief interruption of blood flow to part of the brain, spinal cord, or retina, which may cause symptoms like aphasia, weakness, and visual disturbances but usually resolves within 24 hours.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Depending on its location, it can cause a variety of symptoms including weakness, headaches, seizures, aphasia, and vision problems like scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms can be varied and may include fatigue, weakness, visual disturbances, and speech disorders such as aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Specific forms can include symptoms like aphasia and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by a very low level of blood sugar (glucose), which can lead to symptoms including weakness, nausea, and in severe cases, neurological impairments or unconsciousness.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 deficiency
diagnoses.description: Can lead to a variety of neurological problems, including weakness, fatigue, sensory disturbances, and in more advanced cases, cognitive impairments such as aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when you use or lose more fluid than you take in, and your body doesn't have enough water and other fluids to carry out its normal functions; can include symptoms like weakness and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Brain abscess
diagnoses.description: An abscess is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the body. When occurring in the brain, symptoms can be severe and may include headache, fever, weakness, nausea, seizures, and neurologic deficits such as aphasia or visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.details: A medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: A potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system).

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension (High Blood Pressure)
diagnoses.details: A condition in which the long-term force of the blood against your artery walls is high enough that it may eventually cause health problems, such as heart disease.

diagnoses.name: Vertigo
diagnoses.details: A sensation of feeling off balance. If you have these dizzy spells, you might feel like you are spinning or that the world around you is spinning.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.details: A type of nerve damage that can occur with diabetes. It affects the nerves in your legs and feet.

diagnoses.name: Carbon Monoxide Poisoning
diagnoses.details: Caused by inhaling combustion fumes. The carbon monoxide from the fumes can build up in your bloodstream.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.details: Can lead to neurological problems and decreased red blood cell count.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.details: An inflammation of the fluid and membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord.
